Sampford appeared at Luton Crown Court by video link from Peterborough prison, where she is being held on remand.

After entering her guilty plea she was told there would have to be another hearing to decide if it was indeed a mercy killing.

Guards patrol the women's wing of Peterborough prison, where Sampford is being held on remand until she can be sentenced following another hearing

Neil Moore, prosecuting, told Luton Crown Court: 'The issue that arises in this case is whether she believed this killing was an act of mercy.'

John Price QC, defending, said: 'The only matter is whether he asked her to do what she then did to him.'

Mr Sampford was terminally ill with leukemia when his wife of 50 years strangled him to death at their home in the Bancroft Park area of Milton Keynes. 

Euthanasia, a Greek-derived term meaning 'good death', is where a patients agree to allow another person, usually a doctor, to end their lives. It has been the focus of much controversy in recent years.

Although it and assisted suicide have become accepted ways to die in some European countries and American states, both practises remain illegal in Britain.

Judge Richard Foster ordered a separate hearing to determine the facts of the case before passing sentence.

Murderers automatically receive a life sentence, but if Sampford's actions were motivated by mercy it could affect how much of that she must spend in prison before being freed on licence.

